0s in Egypt and Lebanon, to the 1990s and 2000s in Morocco and Syria.Supporting a historical overview of the documentary form in the Arab world with a series of in-depth case studies, Van de Peer looks at the work of pioneering figures like Ateyyat El Abnoudy, the ‘mother of Egyptian documentary’, Tunisia’s Selma Baccar and the Palestinian filmmaker Mai Masri. Addressing the context of the films’ production, distribution and exhibition, the book also asks why these women held on to the ideals of a type of filmmaking that was unlikely to be accepted by the censor, and looks at precisely how the women documentarists managed to frame expressions of dissent with the tools available to the documentary maker.Case studies include:Egypt's Ateyyat El AbnoudyLebanon's Jocelyne Saab Algeria's Assia DjebarTunisia's Selma Baccar Palestine's Mai MasriMorocco's Izza Génini Syria's Hala Alabdallah Yakoub  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCensorshipzAfrica, NorthxHistory. 0aCensorshipzMiddle EastxHistory. 0aDocumentary filmsxPolitical aspectszArab countries. 0aDocumentary filmszAfrica, NorthxHistory and criticism. 0aDocumentary filmszArab countriesxHistory and criticism. 0aDocumentary filmszMiddle EastxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen motion picture producers and directorszAfrica, NorthxHistory. 0aWomen motion picture producers and directorszArab countries. 0aWomen motion picture producers and directorszMiddle EastxHistory. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Direction & Production.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311078140340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748696079423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748696079/original  a978-3-11-078140-3  Edinburgh Univ